<br>
I work for a 4 hospital system that, due to a change in the way medicare pays for services, went from being $6 mil in the black to $24 in the red.  When this was announced, it resulted in layoffs and slight downgrading of services to the communities we serve.<br>
<br>
Another hosptial in the same county, this one managed by the Sisters of Mercy, closed the doors on the Neo-Natal ICU, and the Crisis Center.  This same organization closed the doors on a hospital in a community which had a near 100% paying customer base a year ago.<br>
<br>
So..when people talk about changing to a socialized health care system, I start thinking about a new job.  Don't get me wrong, I love my job.  I love being able to help people and do my part to provide care and comfort to people.  I am not, however, willing to sacrifice my own life to do it.  Guarantee me that I won't have to take a pay cut, nor risk layoffs, nor see a downgrade in services or patient care, and I'll support Socialized Medicine.  I have as much of a right to maintain my standard of living as someone working in a non-health care field.  Maybe I'm sounding selfish, but I know I'm not alone in that thought process.<br>
<br>
I agree with the statement &quot;Keep what works, fix what is broken&quot;.  Use the Medicare money smarter, investigate a more cost-efficient way to use the available funds to provide more care.  Tear down medicare as we know it and restructure it into something that actually works. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=janusshadowsong>JanusShadowsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 28<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/19/03 11:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Those Without Healthcare Obviously Don't Want It</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>there's plenty of healthcare available to anyone, some people just don't make it a priority in their lives to figure out how. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Hey that works!  To hell with the uninsured.  All 40 million of them.  It's not like they want or need health care, since it's obviously not a priority in their lives.  And they can always go to the emergency room, the pathetic losers. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1850<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/19/03 12:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Those Without Healthcare Obviously Don't Want It</span><hr size=1> Realistically, I think that group of 40 million needs to be divided up into subgroups.  Everyone who is uninsured is not the same.<br>
<br>
1) Those who simply choose not to buy insurance: This includes a lot of young people who think they are invincible and can't get sick (like my sister).  Well, these people make their choice and have to live with the consequences.<br>
<br>
2) Children: I think they should all be covered.  I'm not sure exactly how to do it, but I would suggest providing some sort of vouchers so that they can afford to purchase insurance, ideally through group programs with their parents' employers, but if not, then privately.<br>
<br>
3) People who are too poor to afford it: Well, this group should be small.  The very poorest members of our society qualify for Medicaid.  It's possible that the income limit for Medicaid is too low, in which case it should be raised.  People above the income level where they cannot afford insurance fall into group 1).<br>
<br>
That's how I'd divide it up.  People in group 1 who could purchase insurance but don't, well, to hell with them.  It's their choice.  I think it's a bad choice, but who am I to tell them what to do.<br>
<br>
Maybe I've overlooked some group of people.  If that's the case, then please let me know which group I've overlooked.<br>
