<br>
Also you have somewhat of a crisis in terms of the labor market for healthcare providers in that working conditions are being reported at the same level as wages as determining desirability of the field. IE, the nurse you pay 40$ an hour and wonder why you don't have a flood of resumes for when he\she quits, is more interested in patient ratio and the respect they get from coworkers than sheer pay as indicated by wage level. OF COURSE, there is also the issue that many patients will begin to complain of when foreign health care providers are imported to the US en masse and their ideas of what &quot;good care&quot; constitutes conflicts with patient expectations based on local culture.  <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=626910" target="top">Chopstiks Kungfoey</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1864<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/19/03 8:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Those Without Healthcare Obviously Don't Want It</span><hr size=1> Doctor and nurse pay is at historical lows right now (relative to other highly trained professionals).<br>
